                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;@Lucek because &lt;code&gt;var a&lt;/code&gt; is hoisted to the top of the scope and set to null which declares but does not initialize the variable, then in assignment you have a reference to an undefined null variable which evaluates to false, and set the assignment to &lt;code&gt;[]&lt;/code&gt;. In the latter, you have an assignment to the property &lt;code&gt;a&lt;/code&gt; of the property &lt;code&gt;a&lt;/code&gt;. You can assign to a property that does not exist -- creating it on assignment, but you can&apos;t read from a property that does not exist without a getting a &lt;code&gt;ReferenceError&lt;/code&gt; thrown at you.&lt;/span&gt;

